      "content": "Critics indeed view substantive due process as an application of judicial activism, where judges are seen as usurping the role of the democratically-elected branches of government. They argue that substantial policy-making is a function of elected representatives, and when judges strike down laws under the banner of substantive due process, they may be installing their own ideologies rather than applying judicial restraint and adhering strictly to the Constitution as textually expressed.\n\n\nHowever, proponents realign this argument by emphasizing that when the original text of the Constitution grants rights that are not inherently enumerated but are held to be fundamental to human dignity and liberty, there is a legitimate role for the judiciary to interpret these rights from a constitutional perspective. Such interpretive acts require a judicious balancing, respecting the democratic process while fulfilling the constitutional mandate to protect liberty and equality.\n\n\nWhat's crucial here is the notion of checks and balances: substantive due process acts as a counterbalance to majoritarianism, ensuring that despite the sometimes fallible nature of political processes, there exist safeguards against the tyranny of the majority. It's an embodiment of the living Constitution concept, where some rights may not have been explicit at the time but are later recognized as inherent within the framework of our justice system, particularly as we have learned from",
